# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: billy-gardner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The **1954 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1954.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 26, with the New York Giants and Cleveland Indians as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 51st World Series on September 29 and ended with Game 4 on October 2.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Indians in four games, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1933.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1953 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The 21st All-Star Game was held on July 13 at Cleveland Stadium in Cleveland, Ohio, home of the Cleveland Indians.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The American League won, 11–9, ending the National League's four-win streak.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] In a continuation of the relocation trend that began the previous season, the St.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri to Baltimore, Maryland, leaving St.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Louis a one-team city, and seeing the return of American League baseball to Baltimore after 52 seasons.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The previous American League relocation involved the same franchise, when the Milwaukee Brewers moved to St.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Louis as the Browns, 53 seasons earlier.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The season would also prove to be the last season of the Athletics franchise in Philadelphia, moving to Kansas City, Missouri the following season as the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] During the 1953 Winter Meetings, the National League relaxed requirements for relocation, changing the necessary votes from unanimous between the eight teams to 75% (effectively six).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] This eased the eventual relocation of the Giants and Dodgers to California in 1958.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] On Opening Day, April 13, the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The 1954 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 13, featuring all sixteen teams, the first time since 1950.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 26, which saw fourteen teams play, and was the first time since 1945 that the scheduled regular season didn't end with all sixteen teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 29 and October 2.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (5 in AL, 0 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Sox, Cleveland Indians, and Philadelphia Athletics had two tie games each, while the Chicago White Sox, Detroit Tigers, New York Yankees, and Washington Senators each had one each.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 29 and ended on October 2 with the New York Giants sweeping the Cleveland Indians in the 1954 World Series in four games.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri to Baltimore, Maryland as the Baltimore Orioles, they leave Busch Stadium (where they played 52 seasons) and move into Baltimore Memorial Stadium.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 38 seasons through 1991.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their last game at Connie Mack Stadium on September 19 against the New York Yankees, relocating to Kansas City, Missouri at Municipal Stadium as the Kansas City Athletics for the start of the 1955 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] ABC aired the Saturday *Game of the Week* for the second consecutive year.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired exclusively on NBC.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The **1954 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 72nd season.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The Giants won the National League pennant with a record of 97 wins and 57 losses and then defeated the Cleveland Indians in four games in the World Series.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] It was the team's final World Series championship until 2010.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The New York Giants swept the Cleveland Indians in what would be their final World Series win in New York.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] Their next World Series win would occur in 2010, 52 years after relocating to San Francisco.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] It was the first time the Cleveland Indians had been swept in a World Series.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The only highlight for the Indians was that they kept the Yankees from winning their sixth straight series.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The last time the Yankees had not won the series or pennant beforehand was 1948, when, again, the Indians kept them out (although that year, they won the Series).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-new-york-giants-mlb-season] It was also the only World Series from 1949 to 1958 which did not feature the Yankees.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The **1954 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball's (MLB) 1954 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The 51st edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the National League (NL) champion New York Giants against the American League (AL) champion Cleveland Indians.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] "The Catch" occurred during Game 1 of this series, when Giants center fielder Willie Mays snared a long drive by Vic Wertz near the outfield wall with his back to the infield.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Utility player Dusty Rhodes had clutch hits in three of the four games, including a pinch-hit walk-off that won Game 1, barely clearing the 258-foot (79 m) right-field fence at the Polo Grounds.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Giants manager Leo Durocher, who had managed teams to three National League championships, won his only World Series title as a manager.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants, who moved west to San Francisco in 1958, did not win another World Series until 2010.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was the first time that the Indians had been swept in a World Series and the first time that the Giants had swept an opponent in four games (their 1922 sweep included a controversial tie game).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Game 2 was the last World Series and playoff game at the Polo Grounds, and Game 4 was the last World Series and postseason game ever played at Cleveland Municipal Stadium.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Indians' next World Series was in 1995, a year after Jacobs Field opened.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The National Football League game between the Cleveland Browns and Detroit Lions, scheduled for October 3 at Cleveland Stadium, was postponed to December 19.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was the first World Series since 1948 to not feature the Yankees and one of only three World Series to not feature them over 18 seasons from 1947 to 1964 (also 1959).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Indians, by winning the American League pennant, kept the Yankees from having a chance to win their sixth straight series.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The last time the Yankees had been absent from the World Series was 1948, when the Indians defeated the Boston Braves to win the championship.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was also the only World Series from 1949 to 1958 in which the Yankees did not participate.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Indians easily won the 1954 pennant on the strength of the American League's top pitching staff, leading the AL in team earned run average at 2.72 and complete games with 77.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Pitchers Early Wynn (23–11, 2.73 earned run average) and Bob Lemon (23–7, 2.72 earned run average) were in top form, with solid contributions from Mike Garcia (19–8, 2.64) and Art Houtterman (15–7, 3.35).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Bob Feller, at age 35, could make only 19 starts, and finished at 13–3.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Cleveland also had potent hitting, leading the AL in home runs (156) and finishing second in runs scored (746), although the team managed just 30 stolen bases in 63 attempts.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Bobby Ávila led the offense with 112 runs and a .341 batting average, while Larry Doby (.272 batting average, 32 home runs, 126 runs batted in) and Al Rosen (.300 batting average, 24 home runs, 102 runs batted in) provided the power.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Catcher Jim Hegan made only four errors in 134 games and threw out 44% of would-be base stealers.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants entered the World Series with a top-flight pitching staff as well, with Johnny Antonelli (21–7, 2.30 earned run average), Rubén Gómez (17–9, 2.88) and 37-year-old Sal "The Barber" Maglie (14–6, 3.26).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants relied more heavily on relief pitching with Hoyt Wilhelm (12–7, 2.10, 7 saves) and Marv Grissom (10–7, 2.35, 19 saves) rounding out a staff that led the NL in team earned run average at 3.09 and shutouts with 17.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Manager Leo Durocher used a solid, consistent lineup with all of his starters, except for the catching position, playing in at least 135 games.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Willie Mays (.345 batting average, 41 home runs, 110 runs batted in) led an offense that also featured Don Mueller (.342 batting average), Alvin Dark (.293 batting average, 98 runs), Hank Thompson (26 home runs, 86 runs batted in) and pinch-hitter extraordinaire Dusty Rhodes (.341 batting average).
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Cleveland got on the board right away against Sal Maglie.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Leadoff man Al Smith was hit by a pitch, Bobby Ávila singled and Vic Wertz brought home both with a triple to right.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Don Liddle and Marv Grissom held them scoreless for the rest of the game.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Bob Lemon gave two back in the third on singles by Whitey Lockman and Alvin Dark, a run-scoring groundout by Don Mueller, a walk to Willie Mays and a Hank Thompson run-scoring single.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Mays saved the day in the eighth after leadoff singles by Larry Doby and Al Rosen led to starting pitcher Maglie being lifted for Liddle.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Wertz's drive to deep center field would have scored both if not for Mays' memorable catch.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Wertz opened the 10th inning with another hard-hit ball in Mays’ direction, which again would have required a great defensive play by the Giants' centerfielder but landed for a double.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Lemon went all the way for Cleveland, losing it in the 10th when Dusty Rhodes, pinch-hitting for Monte Irvin with two Giants on base, hit a walk-off home run.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Once again, the visitors started quickly but could not hold their lead.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Al Smith's leadoff home run off Johnny Antonelli put Cleveland up 1–0.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Early Wynn preserved that lead, pitching four perfect innings, but in the fifth inning, Willie Mays walked and Hank Thompson singled, and Dusty Rhodes, again pinch-hitting for Monte Irvin, delivered a run-scoring single.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Antonelli gave himself the go-ahead run by scoring Thompson on a groundout.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] New York had just four hits, but Rhodes padded the Giants' lead with a home run leading off the seventh.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Their other hit came in the sixth inning on an Alvin Dark leadoff single.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Antonelli walked six but struck out nine, pitching a complete game to give the Giants a 2–0 series lead.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was the last postseason game at the Polo Grounds.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] A huge crowd of 71,555 hoped to see Cleveland get its first win, but things did not go well for the home team.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Indians trailed 1–0 quickly when Whitey Lockman singled, took second on a groundout and scored on a hit by Willie Mays.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The run was scored as unearned because of an error by shortstop George Strickland.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] With the bases loaded in the third, pinch hitter Dusty Rhodes hit a two-run single.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] An error by pitcher Mike Garcia on Davey Williams' bunt attempt gave the Giants another run to make it 4–0.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants added to their lead on run-scoring singles by Wes Westrum off of Art Houtteman in the fifth and by Mays off of Ray Narleski in the sixth.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Ruben Gomez gave up just four hits and two runs (a Vic Wertz home run in the seventh and an error by shortstop Alvin Dark on a ground ball by Al Smith), with knuckleballer Hoyt Wilhelm mopping up for the save.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Cleveland's slim comeback chances took a beating as the Indians fell hopelessly behind, 7–0.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The scoring started on a pair of Cleveland errors in the second inning.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] A run-scoring double by Mays in the third scored another run.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants' four-run fifth inning broke the game wide open.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Starter Bob Lemon loaded the bases and was pulled for Hal Newhouser, who faced just two batters, giving up a walk to Thompson and two-run single to Irvin.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants added another run in the inning on Wes Westrum's sacrifice fly against Ray Narleski.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] It was the most unexpected sweep in World Series history, and one of the most unexpected upsets in World Series history, with the Indians having a better regular reason record by 14 games.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was also the last World Series before the official World Series MVP award began to be awarded in 1955, though Dusty Rhodes would have been a lock for the award if it had been introduced yet.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The Giants also became only the second non-Yankees team ever to sweep a four-game World Series, joining the Boston Braves in 1914.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] This was the first of what is currently four consecutive defeats in the World Series for the Indians.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] After the series loss, the Indians fell into a massive slump, and as the Major League Baseball postseason playoff format made its debut in 1969, they would fail to make the postseason during the entirety of the four-team era when only division winners qualified for the postseason.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] They would not return to the postseason until the field was expanded in 1995 to four teams per league, and that season the Indians would make it back to the World Series, but were upset by the Atlanta Braves in six games, which was their second consecutive defeat in the Fall Classic.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] They also returned in 1997, and lost to the Florida Marlins in seven games after being an out away from the championship in Game 7.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Then came the 2016 World Series, which the Indians blew a 3–1 series lead and lost in seven games to the Chicago Cubs, who won their first title in 108 years, which was the Indians’ fourth consecutive loss in the Fall Classic and they now hold the longest championship drought in the majors.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] The only team in North American sports with a longer championship are the NFL’s Arizona Cardinals, who last won a championship in 1947 (as the Chicago Cardinals), a year before Cleveland’s last World Series victory.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] As for the Giants, they too would eventually fall into a slump after their World Series win and be saddled with the Curse of Coogan's Bluff after their move to San Francisco.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] However, the Giants would have much better luck than the Indians during this time.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] They would return to Fall Classic in 1962, but narrowly lost to the New York Yankees in seven games.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] They also returned in 1989, but were swept by their cross-town rival in the Oakland Athletics.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] Then, they would suffer a third straight defeat in 2002 against their cross-state foe in the Anaheim Angels in seven games after being six outs away from the championship in Game 6.
[src:billy-gardner/1954-world-series] They would eventually end the curse in 2010 over the Texas Rangers in five games, which marked the start of a dynasty for the Giants.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The **1955 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1955.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 25, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 52nd World Series on September 28 and ended with Game 7 on October 4.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In the sixth iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, The Dodgers defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first World Series between the two teams to see the Dodgers win over the Yankees.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1954 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 22nd All-Star Game was held on July 12 at Milwaukee County Stadium in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, home of the Milwaukee Braves.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In a continuation of the relocation trend that began in 1953, a team moved for the third consecutive year.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics moved from Philadelphia to Kansas City, Missouri, leaving Philadelphia as a one-team city.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] On April 14, the New York Yankees became the 13th team to break baseball's color line when they called up Elston Howard.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 1955 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11, featuring four teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 25, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1953.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 28 and October 4.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles had two tie games.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers and Chicago Cubs had one tie game each.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 4 with the Brooklyn Dodgers defeating the New York Yankees in the 1955 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Philadelphia Athletics from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Kansas City, Missouri as the Kansas City Athletics, they leave Connie Mack Stadium (where they played 46 seasons) and move into Municipal Stadium.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 13 seasons through 1967, before again relocating.
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The *Game of the Week* moved from ABC to CBS (the rights were actually set up through the Falstaff Brewing Corporation).
[src:billy-gardner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired on NBC.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The **1956 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1956.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the previous season, the postseason began with Game 1 of the 53rd World Series on October 3 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The series is notable for Yankees pitcher Don Larsen's perfect game in Game 5.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] In the seventh iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Dodgers, four games to three, capturing their 17th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1953.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the final Subway Series matchup between the two teams, as the next World Series between the two in 1963 would see a relocated Dodgers franchise in Los Angeles, California.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Brooklyn Dodgers from the 1955 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The 23rd All-Star Game was held on July 10 at Griffith Stadium in Washington, D.C., home of the Washington Senators.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The 1956 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 17, featuring all sixteen teams, the first time since 1954.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 30, which also saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from the previous season.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first time since 1950 that all sixteen teams played their first and last games on the same days.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 3 and October 10.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (2 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Sox, Cleveland Indians, Detroit Tigers, and Washington Senators had one tie game each.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and Pittsburgh Pirates had three tie games each.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Redlegs and Milwaukee Braves had one tie game each.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 3 and ended on October 10 with the New York Yankees defeating the Brooklyn Dodgers in the 1956 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers began playing several home games in Jersey City, New Jersey, playing seven games on April 19, May 16, June 25, July 25, 31, August 7 and 15.
[src:billy-gardner/1956-major-league-baseball-season] CBS aired the Saturday *Game of the Week* for the second consecutive year.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The **1959 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1959.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Los Angeles Dodgers and Chicago White Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers swept the Milwaukee Braves in a regular season best-of-three tiebreaker, for the National League title, after both teams finished their 154-game schedules with identical 86–68 records.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] This was the fourth regular season tie-breaker.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 56th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 6 on October 8.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers defeated the White Sox, four games to two, capturing their second championship in franchise history, their first since in 1955, and first in Los Angeles.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first appearance of the White Sox in the "Fall Classic" since the infamous Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series and interrupted a Yankees' dynasty that dominated the American League between 1949 and 1964.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1958 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time in professional baseball history, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 26th All-Star Game, was held on July 7 at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, home of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 27th All-Star Game, was held on August 3 at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum in Los Angeles, California, home of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Cincinnati Redlegs reverted to their 1890–1952 name, the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] On July 21, the Boston Red Sox became the 16th and final team in professional baseball to break the color line when they fielded Pumpsie Green, 12 years after Jackie Robinson of the Brooklyn Dodgers broke the professional baseball color line in 1947.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox were notably resistant to integration due to team owner Tom Yawkey, and only did so following a lawsuit charging Yawkey and general manager Bucky Harris with discrimination and the deliberate barring of black players from the Red Sox.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The NAACP issued charges of "following an anti-Negro policy", and the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination announced a public hearing on racial bias against the Red Sox.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The 1959 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 9, featuring four teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on September 27, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1957.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Due to the Los Angeles Dodgers and Milwaukee Braves finishing with the same record of 86–68, a best-of-three tie-breaker was scheduled, to be considered an extension of the regular season.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 8.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (2 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox had two tie games.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs, Milwaukee Braves, Philadelphia Phillies, and Pittsburgh Pirates had one each.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 8 with the Los Angeles Dodgers defeating the Chicago White Sox in the 1959 World Series in six games.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The San Francisco Giants would play their final game at Seals Stadium on September 20 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, moving into Candlestick Park for the start of the 1960 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC aired weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series also aired on NBC.
[src:billy-gardner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The rights to air the 1959 National League tie-breaker series were awarded to ABC.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The **1960 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1960.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 57th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 7 on October 13.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Pirates, led by second baseman Bill Mazeroski, defeated the Yankees, led by outfield sluggers Mickey Mantle and Roger Maris, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1925.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The series ended with Mazeroski hitting a walk-off home run in Game 7 and is among the most memorable in baseball history.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Los Angeles Dodgers from the 1959 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] For the second year, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 28th All-Star Game, was held on July 11 at Municipal Stadium in Kansas City, Missouri, home of the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 29th All-Star Game, was held on July 13 at Yankee Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Yankees.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The American League's Washington Senators played their final season in Washington, D.C. before moving to the Minneapolis–Saint Paul metropolitan area as the Minnesota Twins for the 1961 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Expansion would also see the end of the 154-game schedule in favor of a 162-game schedule.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Following the end of the previous season, the two leagues saw their first interleague trade on November 21, when the Chicago Cubs received 1B Dick Gernert from the Boston Red Sox, in exchange for RHP Dave Hillman and 1B Jim Marshall.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The 1960 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and was the last season to use the format by the American League due to the 1961 American League expansion, which saw an extension of the schedule to 162 games.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would use the 154-game format for one more season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 12, featuring all eight teams, while American League Opening Day took place on April 18, featuring the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend since the previous season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (1 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Athletics and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants had two tie games.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the Pittsburgh Pirates defeating the New York Yankees in the 1960 World Series in seven games.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The San Francisco Giants open Candlestick Park after playing at Seals Stadium for two seasons.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at the Candlestick Park for 40 seasons through 1999.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their final game at Griffith Stadium on October 2 against the Baltimore Orioles, relocating to Bloomington, Minnesota at Metropolitan Stadium as the Minnesota Twins for the start of the 1961 season.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC continued to air weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] ABC also returned to MLB broadcasting with a series of afternoon Saturday games.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] ABC typically did three regional games a week.
[src:billy-gardner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Two of ABC's games were always from the Eastern or Central Time Zone, while the late game was usually a San Francisco Giants or Los Angeles Dodgers home game.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Born in New London, Connecticut, Gardner was signed by the Giants in 1945 and came up with them on April 22, 1954, but he could not break into the contending team's lineup.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] In early 1956, he was purchased by the Orioles.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner picked up a career-high of 10 steals, but in his best season of 1957, he led the league in doubles with 36, and at bats with 644.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] He played in every one of the 154 games that season, batting .262 with 6 home runs and 55 RBIs.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] In his career, Gardner also came in the top 10 in hit by pitches twice (1956 and 1957), with a career-high of 8 in 1957 (fifth in the league).
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner wound up as a utility infielder with 1961 Yankees, winning the 1961 World Series with them against the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] In his one and only at bat of the post-season, he lined out to shortstop in the ninth inning of Game 2.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner ended his career with two years on the Red Sox, picking up 70 hits with them in 283 at bats.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Nicknamed "Shotgun" for his rifle arm, Gardner led American League second basemen in fielding percentage in 1957 (.987), including 55 consecutive errorless games, and finished with a .976 fielding mark all-time.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] In all or parts of ten seasons, Gardner batted .237 with 41 home runs and 271 RBIs in 1,034 games played.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] He picked up 841 hits, with 159 doubles and 18 triples in 3,544 career at bats.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] After finishing his career with the Red Sox, Gardner stayed in the Boston organization for eight more seasons as a minor league coach and manager (1964; 1967–71) and major league third-base coach (1965–66).
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] He then managed in the Kansas City Royals farm system from 1972 to 1976, coached at first base for the Montreal Expos in 1977–78, and was a skipper in the Montreal farm system in 1979–80.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner rejoined the Twins as a third-base coach for the 1981 season.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] He was promoted to manager on May 23, 1981, replacing Johnny Goryl, and served until June 21, 1985, never leading Minnesota to the playoffs and avoiding a losing record only once (1984, at 81–81).
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner incorporated young players such as Kent Hrbek, Kirby Puckett, Frank Viola and Tim Laudner into the Twin lineup, beginning the foundation of the club's two World Series clubs to come.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] After a 268–353 record with Minnesota, Gardner received a second chance to manage with the 1987 Royals.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner initially signed as the Royals' 1987 third-base coach, but terminally ill Royals manager Dick Howser, diagnosed with a malignant brain tumor during the summer of 1986, was forced to retire during spring training, and Gardner was promoted to fill the vacancy.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] He was fired on August 28 of that year after going 62–64, and John Wathan took over.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] His career record as a manager was 330–417, a .442 winning percentage.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner's son, Billy Jr., a former minor league infielder, is a manager in the Miami Marlins' farm system, currently with the Beloit Sky Carp.
[src:billy-gardner/billy-gardner] Gardner died at his home in Waterford, Connecticut, on January 3, 2024, at the age of 96.
